        </p>

        <p>
          Thus <m>k = 48</m> <quantity><unit base="pound"/><per base="foot"/></quantity>  and <m>F(x) = 48x</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          We compute the total work performed by integrating <m>F(x)</m> from <m>x=0</m> to <m>x=5/12</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>W   \amp =   \int_0^{5/12} 48x \, dx</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =  24x^2\Big|_0^{5/12}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp =  25/6 \approx 4.1667\,\text{ft--lb}</mrow>
          </md>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Pumping Fluids</title>
    <p>
      Another useful example of the application of integration to compute work comes in the pumping of fluids,
      often illustrated in the context of emptying a storage tank by pumping the fluid out the top.
      This situation is different than our previous examples for the forces involved are constant.
      After all, the force required to move one cubic foot of water (about <quantity><mag>62.4</mag><unit base="pound"/></quantity> ) 
      is the same regardless of its location in the tank.
      What is variable is the distance that cubic foot of water has to travel;
      water closer to the top travels less distance than water at the bottom,
      producing less work.
    </p>

